        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a lively 9-year-old girl with bright brown eyes, curly chestnut hair usually tied in two pigtails, and a cheerful, talkative personality. She attends third grade at a local primary school, where she enjoys art class, gymnastics, and playing with her close group of friends during recess. At home she loves drawing cartoon animals, watching animated movies with her younger brother, and helping her mother bake on weekends. Over the past three days, {patientName} has become noticeably quieter and more irritable than usual. She complains of a severe, burning sore throat that makes swallowing even water very painful, and she has barely touched her meals. Her mother noticed that {patientName}'s neck looked puffy and that she felt very warm; a home thermometer confirmed a fever of 38.9 °C. {patientName} also reports a headache and says her ears \"feel funny,\" suggesting referred otalgia. She looks tired and pale, sits hunched on the examination table clutching a stuffed rabbit, and winces visibly every time she swallows. On physical examination, the oropharynx reveals markedly enlarged, erythematous tonsils bilaterally coated with yellowish-white exudates, and tender anterior cervical lymphadenopathy is palpable on both sides."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:a3610034-ca61-40b5-b6f5-16ef91602ae6",
